<br>
King Thranduil is the King of the wood elves of Mirkwood (or Greenwood the Great as they would name it, Mirkwood only being the name used in the last few centuries due to the corruption of the wood by the presence of the 'necromancer' who Gandalf later finds out was actually Sauron). The Elves are of three different tribes, thus their THREE rings in the first age. The wood elves are a seperate and distinct type/tribe of elf apart from the Grey Elves of Gladriel's Folk for instance. <br>
<br>
Wood elves are far more mundane than the Grey Elves, who are actually surrounded by a visible and palpable aura of light and power at all times. <br>
<br>
More than likely Legolas is simply a warrior who excels in archery. He never evidenced any natural abilites that would indicate him being  ranger (no more than normal for Wood elves that is, which is still a load).<br>
<br>
Of course all elves of middel earth are immortal, so having a few THOUSAND years to practivce your craft can make you pretty darn good at it. Also tolkeins elves were all far more mystical and poiwerful than most elves in your average FRPG.<br>
<br>
As examples, Legolas, while the Fellowship is attemping to cross the frozen pass, is ON TOP of the snow leaving no prints while everyone else is trudging THROUGH the snow nearly wasit deep. Also he is wearing the same exact amount of clothes as he does everywhere else in the movie. Why? Elves do not feel the extremes of heat or cols. They are preternaturally resilient. Elves for tolkein were the ultimate expression of Qualioty over quantity. Not a lot OF them, but all were pretty much SERIOUS melee and magic bad asses.<br>
<br>
As for those who were disappointed with Gimli's showing in book one, just wait until the battle at Helm's Deep in the second film, eheheh. That axe will show it's worth.<br>
<br>
